  { q: 'How much does AC replacement cost in Tampa?', a: 'Most Tampa Bay AC replacements fall in the $5,500–$12,000 range for standard central systems, $11,000–$16,000 for high-efficiency variable-speed heat pumps, and $3,800–$6,800 for single-zone mini-splits. Ductwork replacement, electrical service upgrades, or whole-home multi-zone ductless can add $2,000–$6,000. Every quote is Manual-J sized — no "that\'s what you had before" guesswork.' },
  { q: 'Is it worth replacing a 10-year-old AC?', a: 'Apply the $5,000 rule: multiply the system age by the repair cost. If the number exceeds $5,000, replacement usually wins on a 5-year operating-cost basis. A 10-year-old Tampa system with a $600 repair = $6,000 — time to price replacement. Same 10-year-old system with a $300 capacitor? $3,000 — fix and keep going. We show you both numbers on every service call.' },
  { q: 'What AC brand should I replace with?', a: 'We install Carrier, Trane, Lennox, Rheem, Goodman, American Standard, Bryant, Amana, Daikin, and Mitsubishi mini-splits. Field reliability in Tampa\'s climate is comparable across the top four; pricing, warranty length, and dealer support are the real differentiators. We match the brand and efficiency tier to your budget, duct condition, and how long you plan to stay in the home.' },
  { q: 'How long does AC replacement take in Tampa?', a: 'A same-tonnage changeout with healthy existing ductwork is typically a one-day job, 7–9 hours start to finish. Projects adding ductwork replacement, electrical service upgrades, or multi-zone ductless can run 1–2 days. We schedule around your day and make sure you\'re not without cooling for long — Tampa July isn\'t forgiving.' },
  { q: 'Do I need to upgrade ductwork when I replace my AC?', a: 'Often yes. Tampa attic ducts in use 15+ years are usually leaking 15–30% of airflow to the attic, which Google and EPA both cite as the #1 residential efficiency loss. We duct-blaster test every system pre-install and recommend sealing or replacement based on measured leakage, not a sales quota. A fresh high-efficiency system on leaky ducts is money burned.' },
  { q: 'What\'s changing with refrigerants in 2026?', a: 'New residential AC systems are moving from R-410A to R-454B (Carrier, Trane, Lennox) or R-32 (Daikin, Mitsubishi). These are A2L-class mildly flammable refrigerants requiring updated tools, leak detection, and installation procedures. All our Tampa install crews are A2L-certified. R-410A systems remain legal to install and service; parts pricing is climbing but no cliff is coming.' },
  { q: 'Do you handle permits and inspections?', a: 'Yes. Every replacement includes the mechanical permit (Pasco, Hillsborough, or Polk County depending on your location) and the final inspection. You never deal with the county directly.' },
  { q: 'What financing is available?', a: 'Synchrony financing with 0% introductory rates and terms up to 120 months on qualifying installs. Many Tampa homeowners find the monthly payment comes in below what they save monthly on their electric bill after upgrading from a 10+ year-old system.' },
];

